<p><a href="#sdfootnote42anc" name="sdfootnote42sym">42</a>See, for instance, Pierre Payer’s <em>Sex and the New Medieval Literature of Confession, 1150–1300 </em>(Toronto: The Pontifical Institute for Medieval Studies, 1993).</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote43anc" name="sdfootnote43sym">43</a>By this point, monastic outriders are rather infamous for their less than discreet lifestyles outside the monasteries. See, for instance, Chaucer’s monk in the <em>Canterbury Tales</em>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote44anc" name="sdfootnote44sym">44</a>See Anne Hudson, <em>Selections from English Wycliffite Writings, </em>(Cambridge: Cambridge Unviersity Press, 1978)<em></em>25, as well as Dinshaw’s reading of the Conclusion in <em>Getting Medieval</em>, 70-72.<em></em></p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote45anc" name="sdfootnote45sym">45</a>Actually, the excesses of those in religious institutions were the reason for the Lollard call for the abolition of religious professions altogether.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote46anc" name="sdfootnote46sym">46</a>Hudson, 25. Dinshaw 69. This is in direct contradistinction to Foucault’s formulation in <em>The History of Sexuality</em>, of sexuality in the Middle Agesas constituted around acts rather than identities, as Dinshaw points out later in her book.</p>
