<p><a href="#sdfootnote65anc" name="sdfootnote65sym">65</a>Mary Carruthers, for instance, in her <em>Book of Memory</em> argues that the mnemonic nature of medieval literary culture meant that the modern idea of an Author as locus of meaning and intention in a text was simply nonexistent. Authority was conferred upon a text communally; the more often a text was read or recapitulated the more <em>auctoritas </em>it garnered, until the text itself was an established <em>auctor</em>, not its progenitor. <em>The Book of Memory: A Study of Memory in Medieval Culture</em>, 2<sup>nd</sup> edition (Cambridge: University Press, 2008)</p>
